Most bards (and paladins, mages, and warriors) give up on ever getting their epics. It's not just a personal assault on you.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Point of fact, most bards, paladins, mages, and warriors do not give up on their epic, they just wait for the right time to get help for it.<br>
<br>
I know mages that dont ask for help until they need one more piece.<br>
<br>
I know paladins who are one piece away, and never even bring it up.<br>
<br>
I know warriors who've gotten their epic without a guild.<br>
<br>
I think that officers and guildleaders from various guilds have pretty much summed up our point of view here.  I feel that the bottom line is, our hands are tied unless you can give us a reason to help you.<br>
<br>
Those reasons generally are:<br>
<br>
I'm an asset to the guild, and a key member on raids. This item will make that asset even larger.<br>
<br>
I'm very, very close.<br>
<br>
Tides of Valor is a very large guild now, by my standards.  We have a lot of members who still want their epic, including a few who ask for help when they probably shouldnt (asking for guild raids to get a Jade Reaver).  But there is only so much time in the day, and much of ours is spent on raids that will benefit the guild as a whole, or at rest (too many raids causes burnout).  I try to help every member that comes to me with requests for help with epic, but the fact is that I cant.<br>
<br>
Heck, there's a necro in my guild who got his epic with almost no help from us.  He did what he felt he had to do, because he knew that there was little way for us to help him.<br>
<br>
Beniel, if you were in my guild, and came to me requesting help, I'd tell you to be realistic, and wait until the time is right.<br>
<br>
One other thing:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Well there is really only one epic that helps the guild and thats the clerics..the rest of the epics help the character round out his total offering to a group, solo experience, or raid.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
By definition, an epic that helps a character round out his total offering to a raid, is an asset to the guild, isnt it?  Most epics, from a broader standpoint, help out the guild. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#383838><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub42.ezboard.com/utremainbladesinger.showPublicProfile?language=EN>TremainBladesinger</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Board Veteran</span><br> <font color=#ff0000>(12/24/01 6:47:16 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub42.ezboard.com/fayonaerofrm6.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=734.topic&index=99>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.theunholytrinity.org/cracks_smileys/cwm/big/firemad.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Re:</span><hr size=1> *looks at Beniels application to join Final Destiny&quot;<br>
